Modeling

Building upon the insights gained from the Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) and Data Preparation stages, we embark on the modeling phase to unravel the factors influencing user activity on the Discovery tab. In this context, the term "active" denotes user interaction with a recommended card, specifically through a click. Consequently, the output variable (Y) is the binary isClick variable extracted from the final impressions dataset.

Our modeling strategy involves exploring two distinct categories of machine learning models: sophisticated 'black-box' models and robust, classic interpretable models. The former category encompasses Neural Networks, chosen as a benchmark for its prowess in handling classification problems and capturing intricate relationships in high-dimensional spaces. Meanwhile, the latter category includes regularized logistic regression, decision trees, and ensembled decision trees. These models are selected for their interpretability and effectiveness in conveying insights to the NCM management team.

The overarching goal is to establish the infrastructure for a recommendation system that tailors and prioritizes card recommendations based on the user's likelihood to click on a given card.

For each model, we initiate a grid search to fine-tune hyperparameters. This involves employing a 5-fold cross-validation setup, which allows us to identify optimal parameters by evaluating their performance across different validation sets.

# Defining reusable functions

def roc_auc_curve(y_pred_prob, title, threshold = 0.5):
    # Convert probabilities predictions to binary (0 or 1) based on a threshold
    y_pred_class = (y_pred_prob > threshold).astype(int)
 
    # Calculate ROC curve
    fpr, tpr, thresholds = roc_curve(y_test, y_pred_prob)
    roc_auc = auc(fpr, tpr)
 
    # Plot ROC curve
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 7))
    plt.plot(fpr, tpr, color='darkorange', lw=2, label='ROC curve (area = {:.2f})'.format(roc_auc))
    plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], color='navy', lw=2, linestyle='--')
    plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
    plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
    plt.title(title)
    plt.legend(loc="lower right")
    plt.show()

def cm_print(X_test, y_test, model, title='Confusion Matrix on Test Data'):
    # Print confusion matrix, given the X_test, y_test and the model
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_test, model.predict(X_test))
    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 6))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt="d", cmap="Blues", xticklabels=['Predicted 0', 'Predicted 1'],
                yticklabels=['Actual 0', 'Actual 1'])
    plt.xlabel('Predicted Label')
    plt.ylabel('True Label')
    plt.title(title)
    plt.show()

Grouping of Categorical Variables

Some categorical variables in the dataset exhibit a large number of distinct categories, and a considerable portion of these categories have relatively low occurrences in the data. This situation can introduce unwanted noise to machine learning models and present computational challenges due to the increased complexity associated with a high number of categories. To address this issue, a common strategy is to condense or group together all categories that represent less than a threshold % of the total sample data. This helps streamline the categorical variables, making them more manageable for analysis and modeling, while also improving the efficiency and performance of the machine learning algorithms. The threshold was chosen to be 0.5% threshold, representing 25k entries.

# Define function to plot bar chart 
def plot_bar(data, column):
    plt.figure(figsize=(15, 5))
    data[column].value_counts(normalize=True).sort_values(ascending=False).plot(kind='bar', color='royalblue')
    plt.title('\n'+column, color='navy', size=14)
    plt.xlabel(column)
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    plt.ylabel('Frequency')
    plt.show()
    
    
# Define function to group categorical data
def group_categorical(data, column, threshold):
    frequency = data[column].value_counts(normalize=True)
    if frequency[frequency<threshold].shape[0]>0:
        grouped_column = column + '_grouped'
        data[grouped_column] = np.where(data[column].map(frequency) < threshold, 'other', data[column])
        plot_bar(data, column+'_grouped')

        
categorical_cols = ['type', 'user_gender', 'creator_gender', 'impressTime_wday',
                     'user_province', 'contentId', 'talkId']

# Transform the categorical variables
for column in categorical_cols:
    group_categorical(X, column, threshold)

Balancing the Data

As seen in the previous section, the minority class of isClick (where isClick=1) constitutes less than 5% of the dataset. This imbalance raises concerns as machine learning models tend to be biased towards the majority class when faced with such scenarios, resulting in suboptimal performance for the minority class. In other words, the model may not effectively learn patterns associated with the minority class due to its limited representation in the training data. To address this issue and ensure the model's ability to generalize well across both classes, we employ oversampling techniques on the minority class in the training dataset. This involves artificially increasing the instances of the minority class through duplication, promoting a more balanced and representative training set.

Additionally, we will explore the re-weighting approach, an inherent functionality in various model functions, to further address data imbalance.

In [19]:

Exclude some features

In this section, it is noted that despite being placed before the model fitting phase, it was born out of observations made during test runs of the decision tree. The findings indicated that the model identified impression position, the card's prior click probability, and the user's prior click-through rate as the most influential features. However, upon reflection, it was concluded that these features are closely tied to and influenced by the existing recommendation system.

As a result, the decision was made to exclude these features from the analysis. The intention behind this exclusion is to allow for a focused examination of the actual impact of user and content demographics on the user's activity level, unencumbered by the intertwined effects of the recommendation system.

Machine Learning Models


We start the modeling process by the sophisticated 'black-box' models, namely Neural Network.¶

Benchmark - Neural Network

Balancing Technique: Oversampling¶

For computational efficiency purposes, a dedicated notebook has been established for executing the hyperparameter tuning script, titled 'Neural Network Hyperparameter Tuning - Resampling' and submitted within the zipfolder. This notebook relies on the training dataset where the minority class in the output variable was oversmapled. Quoting from that specific notebook:


We delve into an investigation of hyperparameters to enhance the efficiency of a neural network. The hyperparameters under consideration include the number of training epochs, batch size, hidden layer count, and the quantity of neurons within each layer. We specifically limit the exploration of layer counts to 1, 2, and 3, while varying the number of neurons per layer across 5, 10, and 15. The rationale behind constraining the layer and neuron count lies in recognizing the inherent simplicity of the input features. As most of the input features are binary variables derived from categorical variables through one-hot encoding, a sophisticated neural network architecture is deemed unnecessary. Consequently, our focus remains on a selection of modest architectures to strike a balance between model expressiveness and computational efficiency.

Utilizing a grid search methodology, we systematically assess the neural network's performance across diverse combinations of hyperparameter values. This approach allows us to pinpoint the hyperparameter set that demonstrates optimal performance on the validation sets within a k-fold cross-validation framework.

Our evaluation of hyperparameter sets revolves around two performance metrics: accuracy and the area under the receiver operating characteristic curve (AUC). These metrics provide a comprehensive insight into the model's proficiency in accurately classifying observations, within both majority and minority classes.

Following the completion of the grid search, our primary aim is to identify the hyperparameter set exhibiting the highest accuracy and AUC on the validation sets within the k-fold cross-validation. This best-performing hyperparameter set will subsequently serve as the base for the final model configuration, embodying a compromise between computational efficiency and predictive accuracy."

The code set was inspired by the class work and the following online article: https://www.analyticsvidhya.com/blog/2021/05/tuning-the-hyperparameters-and-layers-of-neural-network-deep-learning/


Import the best performing parameters

The best performing set of parameters was defined in the 'Neural Network Hyperparameter Tuning - Resampling' notebook on the following basis:


When we compare the top two sets of hyperparameters—one optimized for accuracy and the other for AUC—we observe a minimal difference in accuracy, just 0.019%. However, the distinction becomes more apparent when we examine AUC. There is a significant gap in both the average AUC and the consistency across the 5 validation folds, as indicated by the higher standard deviation of 6.445 in the best-Accuracy model compared to 0.394 in the best-AUC model. This leads us to favor the model with the highest AUC. Opting for this model provides a substantial improvement in AUC, ensuring more robust performance across various validations. The slight compromise in overall accuracy is overshadowed by the considerable gains in AUC and the heightened confidence in the model's performance.

# Function to plot diagnostic learning curves
def summarize_diagnostics(history): 
    plt.figure(figsize=(17, 4))
    
    plt.subplot(131)
    plt.title('Cross Entropy Loss')
    plt.plot(history.history['loss'], color='royalblue', label='train')
    
    plt.subplot(132)
    plt.title('Classification Accuracy')
    plt.plot(history.history['accuracy'], color='royalblue', label='train')
    
    plt.subplot(133)
    plt.title('Classification AUC')
    plt.plot(history.history['auc'], color='royalblue', label='train')
    plt.show()

# define the nn model
model = Sequential()

# add input and first hidden layer
model.add(Dense(loaded_NN_params['neurons'], input_shape=(X_train_resampled_no_probs.shape[1],), 
                activation='relu', kernel_initializer='he_uniform')) 

# add other hidden layers
for _ in range(loaded_NN_params['layers'] - 1):
    model.add(Dense(loaded_NN_params['neurons'], activation='relu', kernel_initializer='he_uniform'))
    
# add output layer
model.add(Dense(1, activation='sigmoid'))  # Output - binary

# setup optimisation 
opt = SGD(learning_rate=loaded_NN_params['learning_rate'], momentum=0.9)

# compile model
model.compile(optimizer=opt, loss='binary_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy', 'AUC'])
        
# fit model
history = model.fit(X_train_resampled_no_probs, y_train_resampled, epochs= loaded_NN_params['epochs'], 
                    batch_size= loaded_NN_params['batch_size'],  verbose=0)

Conclusion: Despite the initial promise suggested by high accuracy and a favorable area under the ROC curve, a deeper analysis of the confusion matrix on the test data uncovers a significant issue. The model exhibits a complete inability to accurately predict instances of the "positive" class, where isClick equals 1. Instead, it uniformly assigns all instances to the majority class (isClick equals 0).

We suspect that the choice of the oversampling technique may have negatively impacted the model's ability to discern underlying patterns. Consequently, the subsequent model iteration involves replacing the oversampling technique with re-weighting. This adjustment aims to reassess the neural network's performance, providing it with another opportunity to demonstrate effectiveness.

The results are very similar to what we've seen in the Neural Network parameter tuning using the oversampling technique for balancing the data. There is a more significant gap in both the average AUC and the consistency across the 5 validation folds, as indicated by the higher standard deviation of 1.15 in the best-Accuracy model compared to 0.202 in the best-AUC model. This leads us to favor the model with the highest AUC. Opting for this model provides a substantial improvement in AUC, ensuring more robust performance across various validations. The slight compromise in overall accuracy is overshadowed by the considerable gains in AUC and the heightened confidence in the model's performance.

    model.add(Dense(loaded_NN_params['neurons'], activation='relu', kernel_initializer='he_uniform'))
    
# add output layer
model.add(Dense(1, activation='sigmoid'))  # Output - binary

# setup optimisation 
opt = SGD(learning_rate=loaded_NN_params['learning_rate'], momentum=0.9)

# compile model
model.compile(optimizer=opt, loss='binary_crossentropy', weighted_metrics=['accuracy', 'AUC'])
        
# fit model
history = model.fit(X_train_no_probs, y_train, epochs= loaded_NN_params['epochs'], 
                    batch_size= loaded_NN_params['batch_size'],  verbose=0)

Conclusion: As seen, the performance of the neural network has not improved with the change in the balancing technique. This outcome suggests that, in this specific scenario, neural networks, despite their general flexibility and utility in diverse classification problems, prove ineffective for the given task.

Transitioning from neural networks, we now delve into the realm of more interpretable classic machine learning models, specifically logistic regression and decision trees. We begin with logistic regression, where our objective is to strike a balance that ensures the model's generalizability and interpretability in capturing the underlying patterns in the data. This is done by fine-tuning the regularization parameter to prevent potential overfitting scenarios.¶


Regularized Logistic Regression

In the case of logistic regression, we opted for the re-weighting technique over oversampling to address data imbalance. This decision is primarly to reduce computational complexity, since the process of duplicating entries during oversampling significantly increases the sample size, thus signficantly increasing computational complexity, which we've seen while training and tuning the neural networks. Additionally, we beleive that oversampling, by its nature, might result in a loss of unique information from the original minority class samples, potentially compromising the model's ability to accurately capture the genuine underlying patterns.

Similar to the neural network parameter tuning, a separate notebook includes the script and results of the tuning process using cross-validation approach and grid-search. The best performing regularization parameter was found to be 0.03, noting that a range of np.logspace(-2, 1, 15), which includes 15 values between 0.01 and 10, was tested.

Analysis of Features

Next, we focus on analyzing the features and their associated coefficients. Due to the considerable dimensionality of the features, our initial step involves identifying statistically significant features using the criterion: if the p-value is less than or equal to 0.05, the feature is deemed statistically significant. Subsequently, we assess the magnitude of each feature's coefficient to derive meaningful insights from the results. In order to accomplish this, we must resort to the functions provided by statsmodels logistic regression since the logistic regression model in scikit-learn does not generate p-values or confidence intervals, which hinders the ability to conduct statistical inference.

In [21]:
feature_names = X_train_no_probs.columns 
sk_coefficients = logistic_regression_model.coef_[0]
sk_coefficients = dict(zip(feature_names, sk_coefficients))

# Extract X_train with the preprocessor
X_train_processed = final_pipeline.named_steps['preprocessor'].transform(X_train_no_probs)

# Fit logistic regression with statsmodels for p-values
logit_model = sm.Logit(y_train, sm.add_constant(X_train_processed))
result = logit_model.fit()


# Identify significant coefficients and their confidence interval with p-values less than 0.05
significant_features = {}
for idx, p_value in enumerate(result.pvalues):
    if p_value < 0.05:
        if idx !=0:
            feature_name =  feature_names[idx-1]
            significant_features[feature_name]= [np.exp(sk_coefficients[feature_name]), 
                                                 np.exp(result.params[idx]),
                                                 np.exp(result.conf_int()[0][idx]), 
                                                 np.exp(result.conf_int()[1][idx])]

Optimization terminated successfully.

         Iterations 9

Decision Tree

Next we will investigate tree based models for this problem. Having trained a classifier with a Neural network model, our goal now is to train more interpretable models, to validate our intuition about the behaviour of the users and gain further insights into the possible next steps in the development of this product. Furthermore, we will have the opportunity to compare how the most import features compare with the Logistic regression model.

As with the previous models, the hyperparameter tuning was done in a separate notebook due to computational constraints. It's also worth noting that for the same reason, we had to make concessions in the methods we used. This means it is likley that with access to a cloud based enviroment where we could scale our computational capacity vertically we would be able to achieve higher performance with our model by expanding the search domain.

Of course we understand one of the limitations of the decision tree models is that it can leave out important features due to the decision bias of the main features. That is why we will also explore a random forest approach.
